WEBVTT

00:00:00.720 --> 00:00:05.840
Now at their core, background and workbench jobs are very similar in that they allow you to run

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:11.840
scripts in a separate session. This is a great feature for any long running scripts you may have,

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:18.080
including for example a machine learning training set. It also allows you to run multiple jobs

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:23.920
simultaneously. Now the main difference between background jobs and workbench jobs is that

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:30.639
background jobs run as a child process within the same session and workbench jobs run as a

00:00:30.639 --> 00:00:36.080
new session either on the local server or off host if you're running in a multi-server or

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:42.400
clustered environment. So to demonstrate these two jobs I'm going to first open up the currently

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:50.080
running RStudio session you see right here on Posit Workbench. And in the top left corner

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:56.160
you'll see an R script called long running script. In this script I'm first loading some

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:03.439
R packages so we're loading the tidyverse and then I create three variables x y and z

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:11.519
and I assign them the numeric values 1 2 and 3. Now I did this on purpose so we can see how

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:18.320
environment variables work within background and workbench jobs. Each variable assignment is also

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:24.480
separated by a call to the sys sleep function which simply counts to 10 to replicate a long

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:31.440
running analysis. Then I also have some code here at the bottom which will write the MT cars data

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:39.199
set as an RDS file to my current working directory. So let's first run this as a background job

00:01:39.839 --> 00:01:44.400
which will again run as a child R process in the same RStudio session.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:49.040
To do this I'll select the background jobs right here

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:53.120
and we'll select start background job.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:02:00.559
So I next ensure that the long running script is selected so you can select browse and I'll

00:02:00.559 --> 00:02:06.080
select that long running script exactly what you see over here. And then I can

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:10.240
choose the working directory and I'll just leave it as this current working directory.

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:17.199
Next you'll see the environment option. Now if I click this box then anything I currently have in

00:02:17.199 --> 00:02:22.960
my global environment which you can see over here is empty would be made available to the long

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:30.880
running script. And finally we get to dictate what happens to the results of the long running script.

00:02:31.679 --> 00:02:38.559
So if for example we want to access those three variables recreated x y and z and we want to

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:45.440
x y and z then we'll need to select to global environment. We also have the option to not

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:52.880
copy the results or copy them as a separate results object. So let's select to global

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:59.199
environment and start this job. While it's running we'll get some updates here in the

00:02:59.199 --> 00:03:05.119
background jobs tab. Now if I try to close this RStudio session we're going to get a

00:03:05.119 --> 00:03:10.639
warning here saying that essentially this will terminate that background job if I close this

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:15.520
session. So we don't want to do that. We'll hit cancel and while this is running you can still

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:20.639
see I have access to my console here to write some R code. So let's just give this a few more

00:03:20.639 --> 00:03:34.960
seconds to finish up. And there we go. We can see the three variables we have copied

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:41.600
to our global environment x y and z and the MT cars data set is now in my working directory.

00:03:43.279 --> 00:03:49.440
Now let's demonstrate workbench jobs which will again run in a separate R session again either on

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:55.199
my local server or off host depending on how you have workbench configured. So let me first delete

00:03:55.199 --> 00:04:07.679
the MT cars data set right here and I'm going to restart my R session. So let's first click on

00:04:07.679 --> 00:04:14.240
workbench jobs and we'll select start workbench job and you can see I've been playing around with

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:19.839
a few options here. So I'll select start workbench job and we get the same two options. We want to

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:27.519
select the R script we want to run so I'll go to long running script and we'll select my working

00:04:27.519 --> 00:04:35.600
directory and we'll do the same directory that script lives within. And then you'll also see up

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:42.320
here workbench job options. This allows you to choose things like how much CPU you want to allocate

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:47.920
to this job how much memory and also depending on how workbench is configured you can also create

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:53.839
customized docker images to deploy this job within. So once you're happy with the setup we can go ahead

00:04:53.839 --> 00:05:01.839
and start this job. Now because it's running in a separate R session we could actually close out of

00:05:01.839 --> 00:05:08.799
this R studio session. And if we do that you can see in the top right corner you can actually see

00:05:08.799 --> 00:05:11.760
the long running script is running as a workbench job.

00:05:13.839 --> 00:05:17.279
So let's actually open up that same R studio session we were just in.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:31.279
So we'll click into it here

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:38.239
and if we go back to workbench jobs you can see it's almost done running it's finally succeeded.

00:05:38.239 --> 00:05:44.720
If I refresh my working directory we can now see the mtcars data set is now in my directory.

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:53.679
Now finally it's worth noting that you can also run workbench jobs from within VS Code on Posit

00:05:53.679 --> 00:05:59.519
Workbench 2. So if I go back to the Posit Workbench home page you can see I have this VS Code session

00:05:59.519 --> 00:06:06.880
opened up so I can click on this. And here we had that same long running R script we showed before

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:12.480
and on the left hand side you'll see workbench jobs. And so if you wanted to submit a workbench

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:18.720
job through VS Code we just have to click this little plus icon. And just like before you'd

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:24.799
select your script working directory and you can start this job. And hopefully this was a helpful

00:06:24.799 --> 00:06:32.559
overview of both background jobs and workbench jobs within Posit Workbench.

